This particular generation was raised by parents who punished anything that was too difficult to process out of their children, which is why we must re-examine ways of engaging teenhood without making it look like a punitive phase of growing up.
Parenting models
Society was vastly different then, with parenting models that used violence, which makes it seem as though those who grew up with the violence are well-behaved, but that is not necessarily true.





Many adults who endured violence while growing up have had to deal with a broad spectrum of childhood traumas.
We have to start from understanding that being a teenager comes with an incessant inclination to explore. Teenhood comes with a deep exploration of boundaries, thoughts, ideas, perceptions and experiences, which eventually helps in the growth of a teen. However, the world is dark with lurking danger, which means that foremost, we must collectively create safe societies for teens to be teens. Being a teenager shouldn’t be a dangerous phase of secret endeavours and if it is, it points towards the gaps in society’s moral fabric.
Secondly, if we are going to create a new society for teens to grow up in, we must be willing to think differently as adults regarding teenhood. This requires us to have a contextual understanding that allows us to engage honestly with the challenges of both, playing a parenting role and being a teen in an interconnected world.



