Wayward
 The internet escalates the misgivings of teenhood, compounds the role of parenting and enhances the danger that befalls teenagers. And yes, technology makes it seem as though the current group of teens are from a different planet, which is neither new nor unique.
What is new is the context teenagers find themselves in and are forced to engage with without adequate information or tools. Thirdly, before we are quick to vilify and label teens wayward, we owe them understanding.
We must listen to teens and give them understanding drawn from references of imperfections and complexities of growing up, and what this looks like with the internet in play. Fourth, we need to teach teens, with minimal to no biases, age-appropriate sexual education at home and in schools so they don’t live in angst over curiosities that make them easy prey.
Cultivating healthy spaces for conversations about teenhood that hold no judgement for teen curiosity is a great place to start. So instead of being quick to sensationalise teenagers, maybe we should start having honest dialogues on the nuances of growing up.





